    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="attribution">Paul Edwards writes:</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="43" relname="span">

&amp;gt;In a way this is simply a plea for a broad, balanced approach to
&amp;gt;techno-science education. In another way, it&apos;s more profound than that. My
&amp;gt;Silicon Valley-based engineering students assume that the problems they&apos;ll
&amp;gt;work to solve will be posed for them by the marketplace, via the companies
&amp;gt;they work for. They want to invent cool stuff and then see if they can sell
&amp;gt;it. The idea of interacting with potential users, especially in any kind of
&amp;gt;thorough or systematic way, doesn&apos;t get much press in their world since
&amp;gt;it&apos;s assumed to be perfectly mediated by the market.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="evaluation">

He is so right!</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="44" relname="span"> The problem is, once we begin to contemplate alternatives
to market-mediated modes of connecting needs to expertise,</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="42" relname="span"> things get very
murky.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="27" relname="span"> This is all the more so as, for example, the PC industry, becomes
more and more monopolized (or, at least, dominated by a few mammoth firms).</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="25" relname="sequence">
We all recall the arrogance of IBM in the years of its haughty successes;</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="25" relname="sequence">
now Microsoft is getting into a similar position. </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="10" relname="antithesis">These firms dictate to
the public what will be available, based on the firms&apos; assessments of what
is most profitable (or most conducive to extending industrial dominance),</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="26" relname="span">
not what putative consumers might actually want.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="28" relname="span"> For those working within
specific firms, the gee-whiz incentives are consequently lowered.</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="13" relname="preparation">

In this respect I consider the pharmaceutical industry.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="32" relname="span"> While its
propaganda brags of the sums spent on R&amp;D (still &amp;lt; what it spends on
advertising!),</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="30" relname="span"> we know that a good bit of their &quot;innovation&quot; is not to
bring new &quot;cures&quot; to the public, but to grab patents in order to forestall
competitive products.</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="33" relname="span"> Lab scientists within are therefore relegated the
task of targeting research toward smaller, more corporate-interest goals,
leaving to the side efforts to (excuse the naivete) improve human-kind.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="31" relname="span">

In STS we can teach all we want about market &quot;imperfections&quot; </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="16" relname="background">(I won&apos;t try
to deconstruct the normative notion of successful, efficient market
mechanisms at this point...),</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="40" relname="span"> but we risk probably exacerbating the
cynicism and alienation of the future experts in our classes.</segment>
    <segment id="19" parent="20" relname="concession"> So be it.</segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="38" relname="span"> How
far should we push that sort of thing?</segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="22" relname="antithesis"> We don&apos;t want mercenary experts,</segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="36" relname="span"> but
we also don&apos;t want to risk dividing their consciousness, turning their good
intentions against them.</segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="24" relname="condition"> Until we can change the system of market-idealism,</segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="35" relname="span">
we get stuck in this conundrum, I fear...</segment>
